ment challenges faced by federal authorities, increased demands for access and security post 9/11, and the role of the public in the Mall’s long-term planning and development plans. By taking a holistic view of the National Mall and analyzing the unique twenty-first century challenges it faces, Lisa Benton-Short provides a fluid, cohesive, and timely narrative that is as extraordinary as the Mall itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCity planningzWashington (D.C.)xCitizen participation. 0aHuman securityzWashington (D.C.). 0aPublic spaceszWashington (D.C.). 4aDISCOUNT-C. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066595640uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144263057440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442630574423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442630574.jpg  a978-3-11-066595-6  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles